<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much does the average wedding cost?", answer: "The Knot's 2024 Real Weddings Study put the US average at $33,000, with significant variation by region — Manhattan averages $74,000 while many Midwest counties average $19,000. The average guest count is 117, which works out to roughly $282 per guest. Couples paying themselves often target $20,000 to $30,000; parents-funded weddings average closer to $40,000 to $50,000. The luxury market starts at $75,000 and runs into seven figures." },
  { question: "What percentage of a wedding budget goes to venue?", answer: "Venue and catering combined typically eat 50–60% of a wedding budget. The Knot's national breakdown puts venue at 37%, catering at 22%, photography at 10%, attire at 5%, flowers at 8%, music/entertainment at 6%, rings at 3%, invitations at 2%, transportation at 2%, and favors/miscellaneous at 5%. These add to 100% as a planning starting point — actual splits vary." },
  { question: "How can I save money on a wedding?", answer: "The biggest single lever is guest count. Cutting from 150 to 80 guests typically saves $8,000–$15,000 because catering and venue are mostly per-person. After that: choose a Friday or Sunday wedding (20–30% off venue), have a brunch reception instead of dinner (40% cheaper food), use real photographers instead of videographers, and DIY flowers from Costco or Trader Joe's. Skip favors entirely — most guests throw them out." },
  { question: "Do I need to hire a wedding planner?", answer: "Not for small weddings. For weddings under 50 guests, day-of coordination ($800–$1,500) is usually enough. For weddings over 100 guests, full-service planning ($4,000–$10,000) typically pays for itself in vendor discounts and avoided mistakes. Couples who DIY a 100+ guest wedding without help report spending 200+ hours on logistics, which is the equivalent of 5 weeks of full-time work." },
  { question: "Should we budget for unexpected costs?", answer: "Yes — add a 10–15% contingency on top of your planned budget. Common surprise costs include vendor gratuities (15–20% of vendor totals), marriage license fees, dress alterations (often 10% of dress price), beauty trial sessions, transportation upgrades, and weather-related changes (tents, heaters). Couples who don't budget contingency typically end up spending 8–12% more than planned." }
]) %>

